      "We hosted a high-level delegation led by H.E. Suhail Mohamed Al Mazrouei, UAE Minister of Energy and Infrastructure, who arrived in Astana for the 10th Joint Intergovernmental Commission on Trade and Economic Cooperation and joined us at the Business Roundtable.  Vice-Minister of Energy Sanzhar Zharkeshov, CEng highlighted the key areas where our countries are ready to deepen partnership. At the AIFC (Astana International Financial Centre), 49 UAE companies are registered, operating in finance, insurance, professional and technical services, ICT and digital sectors. As of Q1 2025, these companies have invested over 238 million US dollars through equity. At the roundtable, the UAE delegation included leaders from energy, logistics, industry and technology, while Kazakhstan was represented by teams responsible for market development, grid operations, capital management and project delivery. The presence of senior leadership on both sides demonstrated strong strategic alignment and a shared focus on results. Presentations from both sides focused on concrete projects and ongoing initiatives: capital market infrastructure, energy, –•—ç—à—Ç–µ–≥#AI, –•—ç—à—Ç–µ–≥#logistics and maritime cooperation, as well as new opportunities in the aviation hub, digital asset tokenization, and emerging mining projects. Overall, the roundtable confirmed that Kazakhstan-UAE cooperation is now driven by execution, with clear focus on teams, regulatory alignment, and next steps for projects. I‚Äôm particularly opitimistic about how our partnership is evolving toward joint companies and ventures within the AIFC.",
      "I will be in Abu Dhabi this December for Global AI Show Week 2025, where I will be one of the speakers. The agenda this year focuses on issues that are highly relevant for financial centers and regulators, such as –•—ç—à—Ç–µ–≥#AIgovernance, –•—ç—à—Ç–µ–≥#dataprotection, generative AI for enterprises, and the future of digital infrastructure in cities and markets. The UAE hosts some of the most forward-looking discussions in this space, and I look forward to contributing to the exchange on how AI will shape financial systems and digital economies in the coming years. For those interested in AI regulation, digital assets, or future financial infrastructure, this forum is a good place to connect.",
      "Seven years ago, on November 13, we held the very first IPO on Astana International Exchange - AIX. Our exchange had been registered only a year earlier, and from that moment we built a fully regulated, fully functioning platform from scratch with trading, post-trade, settlement infrastructure, everything. Looking back, AIX became a stage for many ‚Äúfirsts in Kazakhstan.‚Äù I still remember the excitement when the first direct retail subscription during the –ê–û –ù–ö ¬´–ö–∞–∑–ú—É–Ω–∞–π–ì–∞–∑¬ª IPO exceeded KZT1 bn. We launched Tabys, a social project bringing investing closer to thousands of new investors. We celebrated the first million, then the second million transactions executed on our platform and we introduced the country‚Äôs first green bonds, Bitcoin ETF, first Kazakh sukuk recognizing progress of our capital market. Trading volume has grown more than 175 times, from $9 mln in 2018 to $1.5 bn in 2025. The hardest part was starting from scratch and building the platform. What kept us going was our focus on our mission, which is creating an exchange that helps businesses raise capital. And capital isn‚Äôt just numbers. It supports new jobs, new products, and new markets. As we celebrate the anniversary of our national currency, the tenge, and seven years of AIX, I want to congratulate the entire team on this journey. Thank you to everyone who has been and continues to be part of this story.",
      "CBDC, cross-border payments, AI, machine learning, fintech, future of payment instruments: these are among the hot topics of the financial industry today. During the Central Asia Fintech Summit in Almaty, I shared my experience on how we at AIFC are actively shaping the regulation of artificial intelligence in the financial sector. Last year, we published guidelines on data protection in AI, available publicly. We highlighted ethics and transparency behind protecting personal data and ensuring secure storage and handling of sensitive information, understanding how AI systems work with data and how decisions are made. I joined Governor of National Bank of Kazakhstan Timur Suleimenov, Chairperson of the Agency of the Republic of Kazakhstan for Regulation and Development of the Financial Market Madina Abylkassymova, Deputy Chairman at Halyk Bank Umut Shayakhmetova, Chairman of Bank Center Credit (BCC) Ruslan Vladimirov, Head of Mastercard Eastern Europe Services Business Development Division Kutay Ak and Co-founder and CEO of Digital Business –í–∏—Ç–∞–ª–∏–π –í–æ–ª—è–Ω—é–∫ during the panel session dedicated to The Financial Market in the Era of Artificial Intelligence. The traditional model of banking and exchange is becoming more flexible. The financial institutions of the future will be more agile, technology-driven, and closely connected to the real economy. The financial market was among the first traditional markets to adopt AI. For example, robo-advisors support wealth and capital management, whereas AI helps build and optimize investment portfolios. In DeFi 2.0, AI supports liquidity management and process automation. This We also focused on screening authorized participants in the AIFC, including crypto exchanges and digital asset service providers. These companies are at the forefront of AI adoption, particularly in KYC processes, often through outsourcing. We are already seeing real industry impact. Data handling discipline has improved and that is critical because AI is fundamentally about data first, algorithms second.",
      "I‚Äôm pleased to share our new analytical report, ‚ÄúKazakhstan as a Minerals Investment Hub: Unlocking Potential through the AIFC,‚Äù prepared by our experts in collaboration with GWM Capital Ltd. At the AIFC, we view the mining sector as one of Kazakhstan‚Äôs pillars for sustainable growth and a vital contributor to the global energy transition. The report provides a comprehensive overview of Kazakhstan‚Äôs mining industry from its current state and challenges to the pathways for attracting investment through the AIFC. It highlights Kazakhstan‚Äôs rich mineral base from uranium and copper to gold and rare earth elements, and the country‚Äôs growing role in meeting global demand for critical minerals. In 2024, the mining sector contributed KZT 16.1 trillion (12% of GDP) and attracted USD 3 billion in foreign investment, twice as much as five years ago, a clear signal of growing international confidence in Kazakhstan as a reliable and sustainable partner. Early-stage mining projects require both private capital and government support. As companies progress toward JORC-level reporting, new financing opportunities from IPOs on the Astana International Exchange (AIX) to partnerships with SPACs listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange (TSX) arise. The report also highlights how the AIFC provides financial infrastructure and access to capital for such companies. Enhancing financing mechanisms for early-stage exploration and expanding domestic refining capacity are critical next steps. The AIFC serves as a platform for attracting international investment into Kazakhstan‚Äôs mining sector, providing companies with financial infrastructure and access to capital through a special legal regime, the Astana International Exchange - AIX, a favorable business environment, and opportunities for partnerships and deal structuring. With continued improvements in regulation and financial infrastructure, and through the unique AIFC ecosystem combining transparent governance, international legal standards, access to capital, and investor support Kazakhstan is well-positioned to strengthen its role as a trusted global supplier of critical minerals. The global market is rapidly shifting towards growing demand for critical minerals. To meet the surging demand of the world economy, the global mining industry is projected to require at least USD 2.1 trillion in investment by 2050. These funds are essential to ensure a sustainable energy transition, diversify supply chains, and create new mining and processing capacities. Read the full report below and I‚Äôd be glad to hear your thoughts.",
      "Today, I welcomed distinguished guests and global business leaders at the Kazakhstan Global Investment Roundtable (KGIR) 2025, a key platform for dialogue between the state and the international investment community. Organized by Investment committee of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Kazakhstan and KAZAKH INVEST. Under the theme ‚ÄúGlobal Investment Trends: Future Vision,‚Äù this year‚Äôs KGIR brought together over 1000 participants from 50 countries including government officials, investors, and C-level executives to discuss how innovation, infrastructure, and sustainability are shaping the future of global investment. During the panel ‚ÄúFrom Innovation to Sustainability,‚Äù together with my colleagues Baurzhan Kankin, Bakhtiyar T., Christopher Campbell-Holt, Ainura Zhumatova, PMP, CEDR and Ruslan Byurabekov, we discussed how the AIFC (Astana International Financial Centre) continues to evolve creating better conditions for investors, connecting Kazakhstan with international markets, and driving long-term growth. At the AIFC, our mission is simple yet fundamental: to transform interest into trust, and trust into investment. I also moderated the session ‚ÄúLogistics Transformation and the Food of the Future: New Drivers of Kazakhstan‚Äôs Sustainable Growth,‚Äù featuring welcome remarks by A. Kuantyrov, Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Kazakhstan, and joined by Jerome Boyet, Nurzhan Marabayev, Slava Maltsev, Azamat Konratbayev, Matthew J. Sagers, Changwook Lee, and Mikheil Nibladze. Together, we explored emerging opportunities in logistics, agri-food, and technology; the sectors that will define the next chapter of sustainable growth in our region. Within the framework of the forum, 49 commercial agreements are being signed with a total value exceeding USD7.5bn, demonstrating the high level of trust that international partners place in Kazakhstan‚Äôs investment climate. Kazakhstan‚Äôs economy continues to evolve from traditional industries to high-value sectors such as green energy, digital technology, infrastructure, logistics, and education. Across these areas, our shared goal remains clear: to make Kazakhstan a trusted destination for long-term, sustainable investment.",
      "It was an honor to welcome The Right Honourable Lord John Thomas Alderdice, a member of the British Parliament's House of Lords and UK Trade Envoy for Azerbaijan and Central Asia to the AIFC, as well as showing AIFC Court and International Arbitration Centre. We discussed how our independent legal system, based on English common law, continues to give international and UK investors the confidence and clarity they expect when doing business in this region. I was also delighted to show Lord Alderdice our Museum of Trust, which was presented during our flagship event - Astana Finance Days, a space that celebrates integrity, transparency, and the shared values that underpin the rule of law. The AIFC Court and IAC remain committed to providing a trusted environment for resolving disputes and building confidence in Kazakhstan as a destination for investment and growth.",
      "AIFC and Singapore share strong partnership ties. In 2023, we hosted AIFC Connect: Singapore and also signed a Cooperation Agreement with Enterprise Singapore, the government agency for enterprise development, and with the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS). Today, 47 Singaporean companies are already registered with the AIFC, and their number continues to grow. During the visit, I met with leading innovators in blockchain, fintech, and AI. With Eric Anziani, President and COO of Crypto.com, we discussed the potential for developing the regulated crypto market in Central Asia and Kazakhstan, and exchanged views on how global players can contribute to the region‚Äôs growing digital finance ecosystem.Despite rapid sector growth, there is still a gap in the availability of international providers offering a wide range of services. Both retail clients and local VASPs are seeking strategic partnerships with global players to expand their offerings and strengthen the region‚Äôs digital finance ecosystem. AIFC has already established itself as a leading regional hub for digital assets, offering a comprehensive regulatory framework, tax benefits, and strong regulatory support. Now, there‚Äôs also a new opportunity to pay regulatory fees to AFSA in stablecoins.I also had insightful discussions with Laurence Liew from AI Singapore on how AI-driven innovation can support sustainable financial growth, and with James Boi, Co-CEO of GFTN Forums, on expanding international cooperation in fintech and attracting global players to the AIFC ecosystem.I would like to extend my sincere appreciation to the Embassy of the Republic of Kazakhstan in the Republic of Singapore in the Republic of Singapore and personally to Mr Askar Seitakhmetovich Kuttykadam for their support.",
      "I recently participated in the INMerge Innovation Summit in Baku, Azerbaijan, one of the region‚Äôs largest gatherings connecting startups, investors, corporates, and policymakers to turn emerging markets into thriving innovation corridors. Emerging markets like Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Azerbaijan, and T√ºrkiye are attracting global investors thanks to growing educated populations, digitalization, fintech development, privatization efforts, and stronger regional cooperation. Most importantly, stable, transparent, and predictable policies sustain investor confidence. At the ‚ÄúEmerging Markets in Global Investment Trends‚Äù panel with finance professionals Jad Ellawn, Erman Kalkandelen, John Hohos, I shared how we at the AIFC refine our regulatory framework to foster innovation and growth. Recent milestones include the dual listing of Jiaxin International Resources Investment Limited on HKEX and AIX, the issuance of yuan-denominated stablecoins, and grain asset tokenization. Through the Tabadul Hub, AIFC-connected investors can also trade seamlessly across regional exchanges, including ADX, without leaving their desks. I also contributed insights alongside other leading industry voices during the ‚ÄúCustomer-Centric Financial Services: Redefining Trust and Experience‚Äù panel. We discussed how banks build customer trust and loyalty. My key point: when financial systems are well-designed, efficient, and fully operational, clients trust them even without visiting a branch. Robust infrastructure, reliable regulation, and structured processes are essential. With Kazakhstan ranking 24th globally on the E-Government Development Index (EGDI), the country provides a strong foundation for trust in digital financial services.",
      "During my recent business trip to Hong Kong, I had the privilege of meeting with Duncan Chiu, President of the Asian Squash Federation and member of the Legislative Council for the Technology and Innovation functional constituency. Our discussions centered on advancing squash development in Kazakhstan, expanding opportunities for our athletes to compete in regional tournaments, and establishing stronger collaborative frameworks to elevate the sport's profile throughout our nation. Additionally, we explored topics related to the development of financial and technological industries in the region.Kazakhstan became a provisional member of the Asian Squash Federation in 2024. During our meeting, we discussed the transition process to full membership status. This provisional membership allows our Federation to integrate into the regional squash community and develop relationships with our Asian partners.Working with the Asian Squash Federation, we see good potential for squash development in Kazakhstan and new opportunities for our athletes, coaches, and fans."
